and uses them on the relevant platforms instead of only using Linux

vary depending on platform.

I would like to remove two unspecified behavior when document.open

(1) Sandbox flags inheritance. This is specific to Chrome. Removing it

has a trivial compatibility risk: 0.000005% usage

entry.title: SDA: Fix start time calculation when changing timelines.
entry.content:
We don't necessarily know the correct start time when changing

timelines. Thus, if the animation is already running, we should

fall back to using a deferred start time similar to when playing

an animation attached to a scroll timeline.



While fixing this issue, it became apparent that there was an error

in how we normalized time based animations. The full timeline

duration is used even if the animation range aligns with only a

portion of the timeline. This bug does not manifest if using duration

auto, but does appear if using an explicit duration.

Step 3: Introduce kMove type and replace WebStateMoved()

Step 4: Introduce kDetach and kDestroy type and replace WebStateDetachedAt() and WebStateListDestroyed()

Step 5: Replace Will*() with WillWebStateListChanged()

Step 6: Migrate WebStateActivatedAt() to WebStateListChanged()



No behavior changes.

entry.title: COOP: restrict-properties 7/*: tokens update after navigation.
entry.content:
This patch is concerned with updating the blink::Page browsing context

group when a cross browsing context group navigation takes place. This

can take two forms:



- When a local frame navigates, the BrowsingContextGroupInfo is passed

directly to the CommitNavigationParams, for an immediate update.



- When a remote frame navigates in another process, the renderer gets

updated by a message from the PageBroadcast interface. This incurs an

inevitable small delay.



DETAILS



For the local frame update, the passed BrowsingContextGroupInfo is optional and is only set for top-level navigations to a different

browsing context group. It takes the following route:

- RenderFrameImpl::CommitNavigation

- WebLocalFrameImpl::CommitNavigation

- FrameLoader::CommitNavigation

- DocumentLoader::DocumentLoader

- DocumentLoader::CommitNavigation

- Page::UpdateBrowsingContextGroup



When the browser receives the information that a page has navigated to

another browsing context group, we use the PageBroadcast interface to

tell each renderer process holding a proxy of the navigated frame, that

the blink::Page is now in another browsing context group. This goes

through:

- Navigator::DidNavigate

- RenderFrameHostManager::ExecutePageBroadcastMethod

- WebViewImpl::UpdatePageBrowsingContextGroup

- Page::UpdateBrowsingContextGroup



Testing is done in the next patch with the

CoopRestrictPropertiesAccessBrowserTest suite.

entry.title: [Zucchini] Remove misaligned memory access from casted pointers: Part 2/2.
entry.content:
This CL finishes fixing aligned memory access failure brought on by:



*reinterpret_cast(*uint8_ptr)



Part 1 (crrev.com/c/4567104) has treated direct memory access via helper

functions (e.g., GetValue(), PutValue()) by replacing the above

with memcpy().



Part 2 (this CL) treats indirect memory access via helper functions

GetPointer() and GetArray(). Guided by mvanbem@'s suggestion,

instead of eradicating reinterpret_cast use (and making massive

changes to callers), we start by simply adding the compile-time check



static_assert(alignof(T) == 1)



to GetValue() and PutValue(). The prevalent use of

"#pragma align(push, 1)" for executable file format structs ensures

alignof(T) == 1 for these structs, i.e., the compiler assumes member

member variables access may be unaligned, and therefore won't emit

alignment-sensitive instructions that will trigger SIGBUS at runtime.



The check fails if T were multi-byte POD types (e.g., uint32_t).

Previously this happens in two cases, which we resolved in this CL:

1. BufferSourceTest.Get{Pointer,Array}Integral: T = uint32_t, and the

check fail. The solution is to wrap uint32_t into new struct

UnalignedUint32T inside a "#pragma align(push, 1)" block, then use

the struct (and access the internal |value|).

2. dex::CodeItemParser::GetNext() calling GetArray(): The

intent of this call is to skip |code_item->insns_size| 2-byte units,

and if the skip runs out of data, return error. Recently in

crrev.com/c/4568608 we've updated Skip() to return false on "out of

data". The solution is to use Skip() instead. A (passing) usage

of GetArray() is similarly replaced.



Fixing the above eliminates multi-byte POD usage for GetPointer() and

GetArray(), so for now we don't need to worry about them. If the need

arises, we can add some "Unaligned" wrapper template in the future.



Also, add BufferSourceTest.Get{Pointer,Array}IntegralMisaligned to

exercise misaligned (re. 4-byte boundary) access succeeding by using a

UnalignedUint32T wrapper.

entry.content:

calculating the width of the viewport incorrectly and causing the

platforms because my original fix had introduced some perf regressions

that I hadn't confirmed the root cause of. Now we know (explained and

shown in the linked bug) that the original fix was indeed correct and

the separation of logic is not necessary. The performance metrics are

entry.title: Multiple improvements to CronetTestRule and tests in general.
entry.content:
- It's now easier and less boilerplaty to get an appropriate CronetEngine

for a particular test case

- It's easier to clean up resources after a single test case

- It's easier to obtain a Cronet builder of the right type

- It's easier to write tests for additional Cronet implementations,

namely the AOSP-backed one



Prevoiusly, the test rule only returned a flag about which

implementation was being tested without any additional support.

This setup relies on tests proactively checking which implementation is

being tested and altering their behavior based on that. Many tests didn't,

and gave false information about correctness of (mainly) the Java only

implementation.



The new setup isn't perfect either and is prone to reusing resources of

the CronetTestRule if one isn't careful, especially with parallelized test

runners. At least it's better than what we had before, hopefully.

entry.title: Do not DCHECK when a deprecated extension disable reason is observed
entry.content:
Every now and then some Chrome clients report extensions with deprecated

disable reasons (eg. DISABLE_REMOTELY_FOR_MALWARE). This can happen when

the clients were not updated to execute migration code that removes

these reasons from the extension prefs. The GetDisableReasons function

occurs.

This CL removes the DCHECK. Instead, a histogram is emitted that records

the bitmask of such deprecated disable reason(s). The histogram provides

visibility into any potential problems with migration without causing

crashes.

entry.title: Implement "BeforeMatch" behavior in AnnotationAgent
entry.content:
A text fragment targeting text in a hidden but showable subtree will

cause the subtree to become visible. E.g. if the text is in a
,

has content-visibility: auto, or has the hidden=until-none attribute.



This behavior is currently implemented in TextFragmentAnchor. This CL

moves the behavior into AnnotationAgentImpl so it is more widely

available to other users of the Annotation API (e.g. user-notes, Chrome

Companion).



As part of this, we do a bit of cleanup and refactoring. The most

notable is that we no longer force an async break after text matching

unless the match is in a hidden subtree (so we can remove all the

double-rAFs from tests.



Motivation: this behavior is desired in Chrome Search Companion since

they use the kTextFinder annotations to perform a search of the document

to check if a text selector "works" in order to then offer up a text

directive link. This behavior is currently broken since the kTextFinder

"succeeds" as a match is found, however, the offered link does not work

since AnnotationAgent cannot open a hidden=until-none section.



This CL additionally makes kTextFinder side-effect free (doesn't

activate any locked DOM, doesn't create document markers) to make this

use case work.



Bug: 1379741, b/283857616

entry.title: Generate stdlib GN rules from the Rust src tree when rolling Rust
entry.content:
This avoids the need to:

1. Build gnrt locally

2. Then download the roll CL

3. Copy Rust packages to prod

4. gclient sync

5. Run `gnrt gen --for-std`

6. Reupload the CL



In order to have the Rust roll pass the trybots.



upload_revision.py will, when rolling rust, do the `cargo vendor`

step in the Rust git checkout to get its dependencies, install

cargo and rustc in a sysroot, build `gnrt` using cargo, and then

run `gnrt gen --for-std=third_party/rust_src/src` which regenerates

the GN rules for the Rust stdlib from the updated version of Rust.



Previously gnrt gen --for-std would generate rules from the Rust

library found in //third_party/rust-toolchain, but that requires

Rust to already be rolled, so this now uses the feature of specifying

the Rust source tree root to --for-std.

entry.title: [//media] Copy only source size in CopyRGBATextureToVideoFrame()
entry.content:
In CopyRGBATextureToVideoFrame(), the codepath that goes through

CopySharedImage() currently specifies that the size of the rect to be

copied should be the coded size of the destination video frame. This is

incorrect: it should be the size of the source texture. This can

concretely lead to problems when the original size of the video needs

to be rounded up for alignment [1], as in this case the coded size of

the destination frame will be larger than the size of the source

texture and CopySharedImage() will raise an error.



When the destination SI is multiplanar (as it is in this case),

CopySharedImageHelper::CopySharedImage() clears the destination and

then copies exactly the specified rect. Hence this case is not

problematic from the service side.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:media/video/renderable_gpu_memory_buffer_video_frame_pool.cc;l=173-179

entry.title: gpu: Make SkiaGraphiteDawnImageRepresentation work for NV12 textures
entry.content:
NV12 textures are wrapped as R8BG8Biplanar420Unorm Dawn textures for

both legacy and non-legacy multi-planar shared images. Make the Graphite

Dawn image representation work for both cases for NV12:



1) for legacy NV12 images, pass the plane index to the representation so

it can pass it to Dawn as texture aspect when creating the texture

view for the plane and wrap it in a graphite backend texture.

2) for non-legacy NV12 images, create a texture view for each plane, and

wrap them in graphite backend textures.

3) for true single-plane images, wrap the dawn representation's texture

in a graphite backend texture like the current implementation.



With this change, playing video on youtube.com doesn't crash anymore

with or without multiplane video flags.
